\c 31
\s1 The Words of King Lemuel
\p
\v 1 The words of King Lemuel. An oracle that his mother taught him:
\b
\q1
\v 2 What are you doing, my son?\f + \fr 31:2 \ft Hebrew \fq What, my son?\f* What are you doing, \x + \xo 31:2 \xt Isa. 49:15 \x*son of my womb?
\q2 What are you doing, \x + \xo 31:2 \xt [1 Sam. 1:27]\x*son of my vows?
\q1
\v 3 Do \x + \xo 31:3 \xt [ch. 5:9] \x*not give your strength to women,
\q2 your ways to those \x + \xo 31:3 \xt [ch. 7:26; Deut. 17:17; 1 Kgs. 11:1; Neh. 13:26]\x*who destroy kings.
\q1
\v 4 \x + \xo 31:4 \xt Eccles. 10:17; [1 Kgs. 16:9; 20:16] \x*It is not for kings, O Lemuel,
\q2 it is not for kings \x + \xo 31:4 \xt [Hos. 4:11] \x*to drink wine,
\q2 or for rulers to take \x + \xo 31:4 \xt ch. 20:1\x*strong drink,
\q1
\v 5 lest they drink and forget what has been decreed
\q2 and \x + \xo 31:5 \xt [Isa. 5:22, 23]\x*pervert the rights of all the afflicted.
\q1
\v 6 Give strong drink to the one who \x + \xo 31:6 \xt Job 29:13 \x*is perishing,
\q2 and wine to \x + \xo 31:6 \xt Job 3:20\x*those in bitter distress;\f + \fr 31:6 \ft Hebrew \fq those bitter in soul\f*
\q1
\v 7 \x + \xo 31:7 \xt [Ps. 104:15]\x*let them drink and forget their poverty
\q2 and remember their misery no more.
\q1
\v 8 \x + \xo 31:8 \xt Job 29:12, 15, 16; [Isa. 1:17]\x*Open your mouth for the mute,
\q2 for the rights of all who are destitute.\f + \fr 31:8 \ft Hebrew \fq are sons of passing away\f*
\q1
\v 9 Open your mouth, \x + \xo 31:9 \xt Lev. 19:15; Deut. 1:16 \x*judge righteously,
\q2 \x + \xo 31:9 \xt Jer. 22:16; [Isa. 1:17] \x*defend the rights of \x + \xo 31:9 \xt ver. 20; Ps. 40:17; 86:1\x*the poor and needy.
\s1 The Woman Who Fears the \nd Lord\nd*
\q1
\v 10 \f + \fr 31:10 \ft Verses 10–31 are an acrostic poem, each verse beginning with the successive letters of the Hebrew alphabet\f* \x + \xo 31:10 \xt ch. 12:4; Ruth 3:11; [ch. 18:22; 19:14] \x*An excellent wife who can find?
\q2 She is far more precious than \x + \xo 31:10 \xt Job 28:18\x*jewels.
\q1
\v 11 The heart of her husband trusts in her,
\q2 and he will have no lack of gain.
\q1
\v 12 She does him good, and not harm,
\q2 all the days of her life.
\q1
\v 13 She \x + \xo 31:13 \xt [ver. 21, 22, 24]\x*seeks wool and flax,
\q2 and works with willing hands.
\q1
\v 14 She is like the ships of the merchant;
\q2 she brings her food from afar.
\q1
\v 15 She \x + \xo 31:15 \xt [ch. 20:13] \x*rises while it is yet night
\q2 and \x + \xo 31:15 \xt Luke 12:42; [Ps. 111:5]\x*provides food for her household
